# Database
# Format: postgresql://USER:PASSWORD@HOST:PORT/DATABASE
DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres:postgres@localhost:5432/bornastar"

# ── Production tuning (Supabase) ────────────────────────────────────
# Use the SESSION pooler (port 5432). It supports Prisma's interactive
# transactions, which lib/chat-persist.ts depends on for the
# advisory-lock + upsert pattern that keeps concurrent writes from
# racing. The transaction pooler (port 6543, pgbouncer transaction
# mode) is faster in raw throughput BUT releases the Postgres
# connection between queries — that breaks interactive transactions
# (we tried and it errored with "Unable to start a transaction in
# the given time" under load).
#
# Recommended URL shape for production:
#   DATABASE_URL="postgresql://USER:PASS@aws-0-REGION.pooler.supabase.com:5432/postgres?connection_limit=30"
#
# `connection_limit=30` raises Prisma's client pool above the default
# `num_cpus*2+1` (~9 on small servers). Anything between 20-50 is
# reasonable; cap by Supabase tier limits (Free=60, Pro=200 conns).
#
# If we ever need transaction-pooler throughput, lib/chat-persist.ts
# would have to be refactored to drop interactive transactions
# (separate the advisory lock + upsert into independent queries) —
# tracked in README "Scale checklist".

# Encryption key for OAuth tokens stored in the database.
# Can be any string — it is stretched via scrypt to 32 bytes.
# Generate a strong value: openssl rand -hex 32
NODE_SECRET="change-me-to-a-strong-random-string"

# Anthropic OAuth
ANTHROPIC_CLIENT_ID=""
ANTHROPIC_CLIENT_SECRET=""
ANTHROPIC_REDIRECT_URI="http://localhost:3000/api/auth/anthropic/callback"

# GitHub OAuth
GITHUB_CLIENT_ID=""
GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET=""
GITHUB_REDIRECT_URI="http://localhost:3000/api/auth/github/callback"

# Slack OAuth
SLACK_CLIENT_ID=""
SLACK_CLIENT_SECRET=""
SLACK_REDIRECT_URI="http://localhost:3000/api/auth/slack/callback"
